{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"95d037f9-b2d9-456f-98dc-5ebc6da88663","content":"## 2. NuGet.org Setup (Manual Step)\n\nOn **nuget.org**, you must register the trusted publisher:\n\n1. Go to [nuget.org](https://www.nuget.org) → sign in → **Manage Packages**\n2. Select your package (or go to **Upload** → **Add trusted publishers** for a new one)\n3. Click **Trusted publishers** → **Add** → **GitHub Actions**\n4. Fill in:\n   - **Repository owner:** `myorg`\n   - **Repository name:** `mylib`\n   - **Workflow:** `publish.yml`\n   - **Environment:** *(leave blank unless you use one)*\n   - **Ref pattern:** `refs/tags/v*`\n\n## Key Points\n\n- **No API key needed** — the `id-token: write` permission lets the runner request an OIDC token that NuGet.org validates against your trusted publisher config.\n- **No `--api-key` flag** — `dotnet nuget push` automatically uses the OIDC token when no key is specified and the environment provides one.\n- **Trigger:** pushing a tag like `v1.0.0` starts the publish.\n\nTo publish, just tag a release:\n```bash\ngit tag v1.0.0 && git push origin v1.0.0\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"43dd2eae-b4ea-4db5-a753-da7839dd69a6","outputTokens":315,"requestId":"E3C8:3A80DA:1C33AAD:1FB62C8:6A07BF7A"},"id":"2db2e3f1-5ee7-4278-bff5-7c3d1b8d448e","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:51:14.366Z","parentId":"53d0cd00-3446-472a-b68d-d27c982c7074"}
